{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Context\n\nrebar has no general mechanism to apply an idempotent setup/config change to an\nALREADY-EXISTING install. Init-time `_migrate_*`/`_ensure_*` functions (e.g.\n`_migrate_gc_config`) run only at `init`/re-init, so a fix shipped after a store was\ninitialized never reaches it unless someone re-inits — exactly the gap the `gc.auto=0`\nlegacy-store issue exposed (fixed operationally; the mechanism is what's missing).\nDiscovered from the gc discussion (e3d0).\n\n**School B (desired-state / convergent), not School A (ordered ledger).** This class of\nchange (stateless config invariants) is textbook desired-state: idempotent, safe-to-\nre-run, drift-correcting — Ansible/Puppet/Chef resources are check-then-act (no-op when\nconverged; `changed` vs `ok`), Kubernetes controllers reconcile level-triggered every\nloop. We deliberately do NOT build an ordered version ledger (Alembic/Flyway/Rails) —\nthose exist for irreversible, unsafe-to-rerun migrations, which ours are not. The A-tier\nledger (committed store-format version, ordered, fail-closed on too-new) is captured\nfuture work (docs/migrations.md + the sibling `rebar doctor` idea dabb).\n\n## Design (agreed via brainstorm; corrected against a plan-review pass)\n\n**Ensure-registry (`ensures.py`).** A dedicated module holding a registry of ensure units,\neach with a stable id and a **check-then-act** callable that no-ops when already converged\nand reports `ok`/`changed`/`failed`. `run_ensures()` runs ALL units **unconditionally**\n(never gated on a marker — K8s drift-correction discipline), catches a raising unit\n(skip-and-continue, recorded `failed`), returns a typed per-unit result list, and writes\nthe set of cleanly-applied ids to `.ensure-applied`.\n\n**The exact 5 re-init idempotent steps migrated** (the ones that already run on the\nalready-initialized path, init.py:204-213 — these are what reach existing stores):\n`env-id` (write .env-id if absent — local), `gc-config` (git config — local),\n`merge-ours driver` (git config — local), `gitattributes` (COMMIT), `gitignore` (COMMIT).\n**Two units produce a git commit** (gitattributes AND gitignore), so check-then-act\n(read the tree, commit only on divergence) is required for BOTH, not one. The fresh-init-\nonly bootstrap steps (`_commit_precommit`, `_gen_local_files`, `_exclude_scratch_in_tracker`,\n`_ensure_branch_user_config`) are NOT ensures and stay in the fresh-init path.\n\n**Entry points (non-hot) that run the sweep:** init/re-init (always), `rebar fsck --fix`\n(opt-in), MCP server startup (after the --help check). The sweep never runs on the hot\nwrite path or on pure reads. NOTE: `rebar fsck` today exposes only `[--output json]` — there\nis NO existing `--repair`/`--fix` flag (verified: tests/golden/cli_help/fsck__help.out and\nsrc/rebar/_cli/help/fsck.txt), so `--fix` is a clean ADDITIVE flag (a plan-review finding\nclaiming an existing `--repair` at fsck.py:682 is a hallucination — the file is 373 lines).\n\n**Concurrency.** `run_ensures()` runs under the tracker write lock so concurrent sweeps\n(two `fsck --fix`, or re-init races) serialize; combined with check-then-act the second\nsweep sees the committed state and no-ops. gitattributes/gitignore use `merge=ours`, so any\nresidual cross-clone commit races union cleanly. `.ensure-applied` is written as the COMPLETE\ncurrent applied-set (atomic temp+rename), NOT an incremental append — so there is no\nread-modify-write lost-update.\n\n**Applied-set marker + write-path pending-hint (Rails `CheckPending`, hardened).**\n- `.ensure-applied` (WS1-owned: format + write) — git-ignored, per-environment, atomic,\n  a JSON array of applied ensure-id strings; absent/garbage → empty set.\n- `.ensure-hinted` (WS2-owned) — git-ignored, atomic, a last-hinted timestamp for the 24h\n  rate-limit.\n- Write-path hook covers the COMMON mutation paths via `_seam.append_event` /\n  `event_append.write_and_push` (create/edit/link/comment/tag/set_*/sign/transition/claim).\n  It is **best-effort, NOT universal**: `compact.py`, `txn.py`/`transition_close.py`,\n  `delete.py` commit inline and are intentionally NOT hooked — acceptable because the hint is\n  a rate-limited nudge (not correctness); an active user hits a common path within 24h.\n- `pending = available_ids − applied_ids` where `available_ids` = the registry's ids.\n  Computed ONCE per process and cached as a boolean (the registry is static within a process\n  — Rails 6.1's cached-boolean fix; no \"registry signature\" hashing needed). A converged store\n  adds ≤1 file read per process on writes, nothing after; pure reads are untouched.\n- Emit a WARNING (rebar logger) pointing to `rebar fsck --fix` only when pending AND\n  `.ensure-hinted` is older than the interval; then atomically update `.ensure-hinted`.\n  Interval + suppression are typed config (`ensure.hint_interval_secs` default 86400,\n  `ensure.hint_enabled` default true) with a registered env override (routed through\n  `_config_schema` + the env registry, NOT a raw os.environ read — there is a CI drift gate).\n  Under parallel agents a rare double-hint is accepted (locking a nag is not worth it).\n- The hint path swallows its own exceptions INCLUDING import-level (lazy `import ensures`\n  ImportError/SyntaxError) and logs at debug — a write must NEVER fail on the nag machinery.\n- The marker gates the HINT ONLY, never the repair. A fresh auto-init'd worktree is converged\n  from init (WS1 writes `.ensure-applied`) → never hints.\n\n**Accepted trade-offs:** a long-lived MCP server converges at boot but does not re-sweep\nmid-life (drift caught at next `fsck --fix`) — WS4 documents this; a permanently-failing\nensure keeps its id out of the set and is named in the rate-limited hint (no auto-backoff).\n\n## Workstreams (child stories)\n- WS1 ensure-registry + migrate the 5 check-then-act steps + init wiring + `.ensure-applied` (format+write) + typed result/failure contract + concurrency lock\n- WS2 pending-hint: read `.ensure-applied`, compute-once-per-process, `.ensure-hinted` 24h rate-limit (typed config + registered env), best-effort write-path hook, fail-silent (incl. import errors)\n- WS3 `rebar fsck --fix` (read-only default, reports `ensures: N/M`; owns the fsck byte-parity tests) + MCP server-startup wiring\n- WS4 `docs/migrations.md` (+ index/CLAUDE.md link) incl. the long-lived-MCP trade-off\n- WS5 behavioral tests (idempotency, hot-path regression, pending-hint rate-limit/suppress/fresh-worktree, concurrency, no_mutate, absent-marker) — fsck byte-parity owned by WS3\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] An idempotent `ensure_*` registry (`ensures.py`) generalizes the exact 5 re-init steps; each unit is check-then-act; BOTH commit-producing units (gitattributes, gitignore) tree-check before committing (second run → zero commits)\n- [ ] `run_ensures()` runs unconditionally at init/re-init, `fsck --fix`, and MCP server startup, under the tracker write lock; it is NEVER gated on the marker (drift always corrected)\n- [ ] Plain `rebar fsck` is read-only + reports `ensures: N/M applied`; `rebar fsck --fix` (a clean additive flag — no `--repair` exists) heals and is git-level idempotent (twice → zero new commits)\n- [ ] A best-effort write-path pending-hint (common mutation paths; inline committers acknowledged out-of-scope) points to `rebar fsck --fix`; pure reads untouched; converged store adds ≤1 read/process; the hint never fails a write (incl. lazy-import errors)\n- [ ] Hint rate-limited via `.ensure-hinted` timestamp with a typed-config interval (default 86400s) + registered env suppression; fresh auto-init'd worktree never hints\n- [ ] `.ensure-applied` (WS1-owned, JSON array, atomic full-set write) is concurrency-safe; absent/garbage → empty set (no crash, no re-commit storm)\n- [ ] `run_ensures()` has a typed per-unit result (ok/changed/failed) and a defined partial-failure contract (skip-and-continue; init logs failures, never aborts); old hand-listed steps are REMOVED from init_core (no double-execution) and the 5 helpers have no other callers\n- [ ] Hot-path regression test: mutation ops may hint but never invoke `run_ensures` (no git-config subprocess; ≤1 marker read/process)\n- [ ] `docs/migrations.md` documents pattern reuse, the marker-gates-hint-never-repair invariant, the hot-path contract, the long-lived-MCP trade-off, and A-tier future; gc-config is the reference unit"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783571772183444001,"uuid":"02bdc3a9-04fc-482b-825a-4ce41afb3f80"}